1
00:00:02,007 --> 00:00:04,134
(MUSIC PLAYING)

2
00:00:39,085 --> 00:00:40,670
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

3
00:01:26,383 --> 00:01:27,384
STEVE: <i>How does it feel?</i>

4
00:01:30,470 --> 00:01:31,805
SAM: <i>Like it's someone else's.</i>

5
00:01:34,641 --> 00:01:35,892
STEVE: <i>it isn't.</i>

6
00:01:38,645 --> 00:01:40,647
(UPLIFTING MUSIC PLAYING)

7
00:01:57,038 --> 00:01:58,999
MAJOR: <i>The criminal organization
known as LAF</i>

8
00:01:59,082 --> 00:02:02,669
is targeting Captain Vassant,
one of our military liaisons.

9
00:02:02,752 --> 00:02:04,629
- SAM: LAF?
- Yeah, they're high-powered.

10
00:02:04,713 --> 00:02:07,716
We lost contact with Vassant's plane
just after it took off.

11
00:02:08,758 --> 00:02:11,886
We need you to make sure
that LAF doesn't deliver on their threat.

12
00:02:13,930 --> 00:02:16,766
Vassant's plane has already entered
Tunisian airspace.

13
00:02:16,850 --> 00:02:19,436
US military cannot be seen
operating out there.

14
00:02:19,519 --> 00:02:20,520
I got it.

15
00:02:21,062 --> 00:02:24,691
You guys fly low, drop me off,
I fly up to intercept.

16
00:02:24,774 --> 00:02:26,151
No treaties violated.

17
00:02:26,234 --> 00:02:28,653
First Lieutenant Torres,
our intel officer,

18
00:02:28,737 --> 00:02:30,113
will be helping on the ground.

19
00:02:30,196 --> 00:02:32,741
And Sam, this has to be subtle.

20
00:02:33,533 --> 00:02:35,243
Subtle. Got it.

21
00:02:47,714 --> 00:02:49,382
Sam, Torres here.

22
00:02:49,924 --> 00:02:52,052
Sending intel to your HUD right now.

23
00:02:55,889 --> 00:02:58,016
<i>I'll be your boots on the ground, sir.</i>

24
00:03:03,772 --> 00:03:06,441
I got eyes on a plane. Any sign of LAF?

25
00:03:06,524 --> 00:03:09,611
TORRES: <i>Nah. Nothing yet.
But I'll keep tracking the chatter.</i>

26
00:03:09,694 --> 00:03:11,363
(PROPELLERS ROARING)

27
00:03:19,454 --> 00:03:20,955
They've already hijacked the plane.

28
00:03:22,332 --> 00:03:24,167
Oh, we're gonna need to call some people.

29
00:03:25,794 --> 00:03:27,128
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

30
00:03:30,590 --> 00:03:32,300
Did you see that?

31
00:03:33,468 --> 00:03:35,220
I just saw a man on the windshield.

32
00:03:37,180 --> 00:03:38,056
Louie...

33
00:03:38,765 --> 00:03:40,642
I'm gonna kill you!

34
00:03:41,476 --> 00:03:43,520
(FALCON IN ENGLISH)
Okay, switching to plan B.

35
00:03:46,231 --> 00:03:47,941
(BOTH GRUNTING)

36
00:03:48,024 --> 00:03:49,025
GEORGES: Hey!

37
00:03:50,318 --> 00:03:52,112
(IN FRENCH) Stop his flopping!

38
00:03:52,779 --> 00:03:54,572
- (GRUNTING)
- (MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

39
00:03:55,115 --> 00:03:56,616
He's like a fish, right?

40
00:03:57,492 --> 00:03:59,577
Maybe we should gut him here.

41
00:04:02,247 --> 00:04:03,790
(FALCON IN ENGLISH) Redwing, engage.

42
00:04:09,045 --> 00:04:10,213
(PULSING)

43
00:04:16,719 --> 00:04:17,720
(VASSANT GROANS)

44
00:04:19,013 --> 00:04:20,014
(BEEPS)

45
00:04:21,516 --> 00:04:22,559
(GRUNTS)

46
00:04:23,435 --> 00:04:24,727
- (GRUNTS)
- (SCREAMS)

47
00:04:26,688 --> 00:04:27,981
(ALL GRUNTING)

48
00:04:30,775 --> 00:04:31,818
(SCREAMS)

49
00:04:31,901 --> 00:04:33,069
(BULLETS RICOCHETING)

50
00:04:39,868 --> 00:04:40,994
(ENGINE WHIRRING)

51
00:04:49,794 --> 00:04:51,421
(BEEPING)

52
00:04:56,384 --> 00:04:58,511
Captain Vassant?
Let's get you out of here.

53
00:04:59,429 --> 00:05:00,805
(GRUNTS)

54
00:05:02,348 --> 00:05:04,184
(BOTH GRUNTING)

55
00:05:12,275 --> 00:05:13,526
(GEORGES YELLS)

56
00:05:14,777 --> 00:05:15,945
(BOTH GRUNTING)

57
00:05:19,324 --> 00:05:20,867
Sam?

58
00:05:33,796 --> 00:05:35,131
(VASSANT SCREAMS)

59
00:05:47,393 --> 00:05:48,603
Oh!

60
00:05:48,686 --> 00:05:49,979
(LAUGHS)

61
00:05:54,776 --> 00:05:57,320
(VASSANT SCREAMS)

62
00:05:59,739 --> 00:06:01,032
(GUNSHOTS)

63
00:06:04,869 --> 00:06:06,746
(MAN SCREAMS)

64
00:06:27,725 --> 00:06:28,768
(GRUNTS)

65
00:06:32,814 --> 00:06:34,148
(HELICOPTER APPROACHING)

66
00:06:34,232 --> 00:06:35,984
(MACHINE GUN FIRING)

67
00:06:43,575 --> 00:06:45,577
Redwing, get 'em off our ass!

68
00:07:10,602 --> 00:07:11,894
(MAN SCREAMS)

69
00:07:11,978 --> 00:07:13,062
(EXPLOSION)

70
00:07:27,035 --> 00:07:28,036
(FALCON GRUNTS)

71
00:07:29,412 --> 00:07:30,788
(MAN GRUNTING)

72
00:07:31,623 --> 00:07:33,207
(GRUNTS)

73
00:07:36,336 --> 00:07:38,379
Keep going! We're close!

74
00:07:38,921 --> 00:07:41,466
If we get to the border,
he's not gonna follow.

75
00:07:41,549 --> 00:07:42,884
(CLICKING)

76
00:07:42,967 --> 00:07:44,552
- What's up?
- (GRUNTS)

77
00:07:44,636 --> 00:07:46,095
- (GUNSHOTS)
- (GRUNTS)

78
00:07:46,888 --> 00:07:48,723
- (SCREAMS)
- (GRUNTS)

79
00:07:48,806 --> 00:07:49,849
(SCREAMS) No!

80
00:07:52,644 --> 00:07:53,895
(GRUNTS)

81
00:07:56,981 --> 00:07:57,982
- (BEEPS)
- (EXPLOSION)

82
00:08:02,403 --> 00:08:03,613
(BEEPING)

83
00:08:04,322 --> 00:08:07,367
All right, heads up!
You're about to fly into Libyan airspace.

84
00:08:07,450 --> 00:08:09,327
FALCON: And I assume
they have a problem with that.

85
00:08:09,410 --> 00:08:11,579
Yeah, yeah. A big problem. A big problem.

86
00:08:18,753 --> 00:08:20,963
- FALCON: How long I got?
- TORRES: <i>Ninety seconds.</i>

87
00:08:21,047 --> 00:08:22,173
(BEEPS)

88
00:08:25,051 --> 00:08:26,135
(HELICOPTER HOVERING)

89
00:08:46,823 --> 00:08:49,117
Aw, shit. He's outnumbered.

90
00:08:49,826 --> 00:08:50,952
(EXPLOSIONS)

91
00:08:56,708 --> 00:08:58,000
(GRUNTS)

92
00:09:00,670 --> 00:09:01,796
(GRUNTS)

93
00:09:20,106 --> 00:09:21,524
Sam, we gotta fall back!

94
00:09:21,607 --> 00:09:24,610
We got to call it off!
We gotta find another way!

95
00:09:26,487 --> 00:09:27,822
(BEEPS)

96
00:09:27,905 --> 00:09:29,407
I just did.

97
00:09:32,160 --> 00:09:33,619
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

98
00:09:35,121 --> 00:09:36,456
(GRUNTS)

99
00:09:39,959 --> 00:09:40,960
<i>Merde!</i>

100
00:09:41,627 --> 00:09:43,212
(SCREAMS)

101
00:09:48,551 --> 00:09:49,761
(CHEERS)

102
00:09:51,429 --> 00:09:52,680
Whoo!

103
00:09:52,764 --> 00:09:53,973
Yeah!

104
00:10:01,147 --> 00:10:02,273
( INDISTINCT CHATTER)

105
00:10:19,248 --> 00:10:20,833
- (SAM IN ENGLISH) Thanks.
- (TORRES SIGHS)

106
00:10:22,084 --> 00:10:23,961
You could try to reroute that
to the other...

107
00:10:24,045 --> 00:10:25,171
Hey, could you not?

108
00:10:25,254 --> 00:10:26,255
Oh. (CHUCKLES)

109
00:10:27,548 --> 00:10:30,343
I've been working with the Air Force
for six months now.

110
00:10:30,426 --> 00:10:33,054
Every time ops touches him,
he gets all glitchy.

111
00:10:33,137 --> 00:10:34,764
Well, you know, those poor techs

112
00:10:34,847 --> 00:10:37,016
can't keep up
with a billion returning IP addresses

113
00:10:37,099 --> 00:10:40,061
- and your sick-ass Stark-level tech.
- (BOTH CHUCKLE)

114
00:10:40,770 --> 00:10:42,563
MAN: Hey, Avengers.

115
00:10:42,647 --> 00:10:44,065
(IN ARABIC) Hello!

116
00:10:45,107 --> 00:10:46,526
You brought my wife back to me.

117
00:10:46,818 --> 00:10:47,693
Thank you.

118
00:10:48,194 --> 00:10:51,322
Always happy to help, sir.

119
00:10:52,907 --> 00:10:54,116
(IN ENGLISH) He knows Arabic.

120
00:10:54,200 --> 00:10:56,035
Wait, can you say that again?
Hold on a sec.

121
00:10:56,118 --> 00:10:58,412
- All right. Come on.
- (BOTH CHUCKLE)

122
00:10:58,496 --> 00:11:02,208
TORRES: Anyway, these LAF crews, man,

123
00:11:02,291 --> 00:11:05,253
they're tryin' to take advantage of
all the chaos and make some money.

124
00:11:05,336 --> 00:11:07,463
And that I get, but there's...

125
00:11:07,547 --> 00:11:08,631
(BEEPS)

126
00:11:08,714 --> 00:11:10,341
Oh, bam! Right there!

127
00:11:10,424 --> 00:11:12,718
You see these guys?
They're guys you gotta worry about.

128
00:11:12,802 --> 00:11:15,638
I've been stumbling onto
their manifestos on message boards.

129
00:11:15,721 --> 00:11:17,098
They're called the Flag Smashers.

130
00:11:17,181 --> 00:11:19,767
Is that a new thing?
Bad guys give themselves bad names.

131
00:11:19,851 --> 00:11:21,769
There's a lot worse names than that one.

132
00:11:22,311 --> 00:11:26,816
But basically, they think that
the world was better during The Blip.

133
00:11:27,859 --> 00:11:29,402
Trust me, it wasn't.

134
00:11:29,485 --> 00:11:33,072
Trust me. Every time something
gets better for one group,

135
00:11:33,155 --> 00:11:34,490
it gets worse for another.

136
00:11:34,574 --> 00:11:39,120
Yeah. Essentially, these people, they want
a world that's unified without borders.

137
00:11:39,203 --> 00:11:41,455
So, you could see
why a lot of people are into that.

138
00:11:42,373 --> 00:11:44,584
Yeah, but keep an eye on it.

139
00:11:45,251 --> 00:11:47,461
If anything gets serious, you let me know.

140
00:11:47,545 --> 00:11:48,880
No doubt. I'll... I'll, uh...

141
00:11:48,963 --> 00:11:51,966
I'll track the online chatter,
see what they're saying. Yeah.

142
00:11:52,049 --> 00:11:53,426
I do gotta ask you, though,

143
00:11:53,509 --> 00:11:57,263
'cause online there's just been
a lot of stuff about Steve, actually.

144
00:11:57,346 --> 00:11:59,599
Um, crazy, crazy conspiracy theories.

145
00:11:59,682 --> 00:12:01,017
So, some people...

146
00:12:01,100 --> 00:12:05,813
Some people, they think
that he's in a secret base on the moon

147
00:12:05,897 --> 00:12:07,565
looking down over us.

148
00:12:07,648 --> 00:12:09,358
Yeah. Well, I can assure you,

149
00:12:09,442 --> 00:12:11,569
those people,
you don't have to take seriously.

150
00:12:11,652 --> 00:12:14,322
But you didn't, like...
( IMITATES FLYING SOUND)

151
00:12:14,405 --> 00:12:16,324
Fly him to the moon?

152
00:12:16,407 --> 00:12:17,992
- Nah.
- Oh...

153
00:12:18,743 --> 00:12:19,994
Had to check.

154
00:12:20,661 --> 00:12:22,413
Oh, oh, I got you, man.

155
00:12:22,496 --> 00:12:25,124
- Thanks. I'll get you back next time.
- All right.

156
00:12:29,128 --> 00:12:31,255
- So, where are you off to?
- Washington.

157
00:12:32,173 --> 00:12:33,549
What are you doin' there?

158
00:12:34,967 --> 00:12:36,385
Moon stuff.

159
00:12:37,970 --> 00:12:39,096
Oh!

160
00:12:42,642 --> 00:12:45,019
SAM: Steve represented
the best in all of us.

161
00:12:46,020 --> 00:12:49,190
Courageous, righteous, hopeful.

162
00:12:51,275 --> 00:12:53,486
And he mastered posing stoically.

163
00:12:53,569 --> 00:12:54,612
(ALL CHUCKLE)

164
00:12:56,030 --> 00:12:57,949
The world has been forever changed.

165
00:12:58,032 --> 00:12:59,033
(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING)

166
00:13:00,868 --> 00:13:02,411
A few months ago,

167
00:13:02,495 --> 00:13:06,207
billions of people
reappeared after five years away,

168
00:13:07,208 --> 00:13:09,043
sending the world into turmoil.

169
00:13:11,379 --> 00:13:13,714
We need new heroes.

170
00:13:16,467 --> 00:13:18,844
Ones suited for the times we're in.

171
00:13:20,471 --> 00:13:21,722
Symbols...

172
00:13:23,808 --> 00:13:26,894
are nothing without the women and men
that give them meaning.

173
00:13:27,645 --> 00:13:29,563
And this thing... (CHUCKLES)

174
00:13:30,815 --> 00:13:32,191
(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING)

175
00:13:35,569 --> 00:13:38,280
I don't know if there's ever been
a greater symbol.

176
00:13:38,990 --> 00:13:41,283
But it's more about the man
who propped it up,

177
00:13:41,951 --> 00:13:43,077
and he's gone.

178
00:13:44,912 --> 00:13:49,333
So, today we honor Steve's legacy.
But also, we look to the future.

179
00:13:53,504 --> 00:13:55,172
So, thank you, Captain America.

180
00:13:58,926 --> 00:14:00,469
But this belongs to you.

181
00:14:01,929 --> 00:14:03,597
(APPLAUSE)

182
00:14:21,907 --> 00:14:24,493
MAN: <i>Thanks again for coming forward
with the shield, Sam.</i>

183
00:14:24,577 --> 00:14:25,911
It was the right decision.

184
00:14:30,624 --> 00:14:31,625
Take a walk?

185
00:14:33,544 --> 00:14:35,171
SAM: <i>Yeah, I've been at home.</i>

186
00:14:35,755 --> 00:14:37,882
My sister and my nephews, man.

187
00:14:37,965 --> 00:14:41,510
When I left, they were babies.
I come back and they're little men.

188
00:14:41,594 --> 00:14:43,012
- It's crazy, you know?
- Yeah.

189
00:14:43,095 --> 00:14:45,264
Well, you should bring 'em out
to D.C. sometime.

190
00:14:45,347 --> 00:14:46,557
I'll teach 'em how to fly.

191
00:14:47,266 --> 00:14:49,351
- You know, I mean, the right way.
- (SAM CHUCKLES)

192
00:14:49,435 --> 00:14:51,979
RHODES: Crazy that nobody's
gonna be carryin' the shield.

193
00:14:52,063 --> 00:14:54,273
SAM: Hey, we went
for 70 years without anybody

194
00:14:54,356 --> 00:14:55,941
carryin' it when Steve was on ice.

195
00:14:56,025 --> 00:14:57,401
So, I think we'll be all right.

196
00:14:57,485 --> 00:14:59,445
RHODES: That was a different time, Sam.

197
00:15:01,155 --> 00:15:02,698
I see you're gonna make me ask.

198
00:15:06,619 --> 00:15:08,329
Why didn't you take up the mantle?

199
00:15:11,165 --> 00:15:13,292
When Steve first told me about the shield,

200
00:15:14,418 --> 00:15:16,295
the first words I said were,

201
00:15:17,254 --> 00:15:19,465
"It feels like it belongs
to someone else."

202
00:15:19,548 --> 00:15:20,716
Hmm.

203
00:15:22,343 --> 00:15:23,969
That someone else is Steve.

204
00:15:26,806 --> 00:15:28,724
RHODES: World's a crazy place right now.

205
00:15:30,267 --> 00:15:31,352
People are...

206
00:15:33,771 --> 00:15:35,064
Well, nobody's stable.

207
00:15:37,441 --> 00:15:39,527
Allies are now enemies.

208
00:15:39,610 --> 00:15:42,446
Alliances are all torn apart.

209
00:15:44,573 --> 00:15:45,741
The world's broken.

210
00:15:46,992 --> 00:15:49,411
Everybody's just looking
for somebody to fix it.

211
00:15:50,037 --> 00:15:51,163
SAM: Yeah.

212
00:16:01,006 --> 00:16:02,258
It's a new day, brother.

213
00:16:07,012 --> 00:16:08,013
I'll be in touch.

214
00:16:27,032 --> 00:16:29,160
(LAUGHS) I mean... Thank you.

215
00:16:30,244 --> 00:16:32,955
- Oh... Well, that's done.
- WOMAN: Yeah.

216
00:16:33,789 --> 00:16:35,249
Half hour before last call?

217
00:16:36,125 --> 00:16:38,627
I can't, guys.
I have to prep for tomorrow's session.

218
00:16:38,711 --> 00:16:39,879
- Really?
- You...

219
00:16:39,962 --> 00:16:41,046
Ooh! (CHUCKLES)

220
00:16:57,396 --> 00:16:58,772
(GRUNTS)

221
00:17:00,941 --> 00:17:02,109
(SCREAMS)

222
00:17:03,569 --> 00:17:05,029
(GRUNTS)

223
00:17:05,112 --> 00:17:06,113
(SPEAKING RUSSIAN)

224
00:17:06,906 --> 00:17:07,948
(GUNS FIRING)

225
00:17:11,327 --> 00:17:12,328
(GROANS)

226
00:17:12,411 --> 00:17:13,871
(GRUNTS)

227
00:17:29,845 --> 00:17:31,013
Hail HYDRA.

228
00:17:31,096 --> 00:17:32,514
(CHOKING)

229
00:17:36,101 --> 00:17:37,228
(FAINT RATTLING)

230
00:17:43,025 --> 00:17:44,026
MAN: Shit.

231
00:17:45,527 --> 00:17:46,737
(BREATH TREMBLING)

232
00:17:54,787 --> 00:17:56,038
MAN: Please.

233
00:17:56,121 --> 00:17:57,248
(PANTING)

234
00:17:58,290 --> 00:18:00,125
(STUTTERS) I didn't see anything.

235
00:18:01,126 --> 00:18:02,711
I didn't see anything.

236
00:18:03,587 --> 00:18:04,880
I didn't see anything.

237
00:18:06,465 --> 00:18:07,466
(GUNSHOT)

238
00:18:08,300 --> 00:18:09,802
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

239
00:18:14,139 --> 00:18:16,809
DR. RAYNOR: <i>So, Mr. Barnes,
are you still having nightmares?</i>

240
00:18:21,146 --> 00:18:22,690
James, I asked you a question.

241
00:18:22,773 --> 00:18:24,316
Are you still having nightmares?

242
00:18:27,444 --> 00:18:28,445
No.

243
00:18:29,280 --> 00:18:32,366
We've been doing this long enough
that I can tell when you're lying.

244
00:18:32,449 --> 00:18:34,410
Well, you seem a little off today.

245
00:18:35,327 --> 00:18:36,787
Did something happen recently?

246
00:18:39,873 --> 00:18:40,874
No.

247
00:18:41,750 --> 00:18:43,043
You're a civilian now.

248
00:18:43,585 --> 00:18:48,424
With your history, the government
needs to know that you're not gonna...

249
00:18:53,679 --> 00:18:55,931
It's a condition of your pardon.

250
00:18:56,598 --> 00:18:59,101
So, tell me about
your most recent nightmare.

251
00:19:00,644 --> 00:19:02,021
I didn't have a nightmare.

252
00:19:03,772 --> 00:19:07,067
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

253
00:19:07,860 --> 00:19:09,403
BUCKY: Oh, come on. Really?

254
00:19:09,486 --> 00:19:11,238
You're gonna do the notebook thing?

255
00:19:11,322 --> 00:19:13,073
Why? It's passive aggressive.

256
00:19:13,782 --> 00:19:15,034
You don't talk. I write.

257
00:19:15,117 --> 00:19:17,411
(SIGHS) Okay. Okay.

258
00:19:18,787 --> 00:19:21,457
I crossed a name off
the list of my amends yesterday.

259
00:19:22,207 --> 00:19:25,210
Don't worry. I used all your three rules.

260
00:19:25,794 --> 00:19:27,629
Senator Atwood.

261
00:19:28,797 --> 00:19:31,050
<i>She was a HYDRA pawn for years.</i>

262
00:19:32,343 --> 00:19:34,803
<i>Helped her get into office
when I was the Winter Soldier.</i>

263
00:19:37,598 --> 00:19:38,599
(BEEPS)

264
00:19:39,641 --> 00:19:41,060
BUCKY: <i>And after HYDRA disbanded,</i>

265
00:19:41,143 --> 00:19:43,812
she continued to abuse
the power I gave her.

266
00:19:44,938 --> 00:19:46,231
ATWOOD: <i>Make this go away.</i>

267
00:19:47,191 --> 00:19:52,738
If Congressman Lockhart wants to speak up,
silence him for good.

268
00:19:52,821 --> 00:19:57,117
So, rule number one,
you can't do anything illegal.

269
00:19:58,744 --> 00:20:00,287
(ENGINE STARTS)

270
00:20:00,371 --> 00:20:01,997
What the hell?

271
00:20:02,081 --> 00:20:03,582
(TIRES SCREECH)

272
00:20:03,665 --> 00:20:06,710
BUCKY: <i>All I did was give some intel
to the aide to convict her.</i>

273
00:20:06,794 --> 00:20:08,504
And I wasn't involved in anything else.

274
00:20:09,505 --> 00:20:10,631
(TIRES SCREECHING)

275
00:20:12,883 --> 00:20:14,051
(SOBS)

276
00:20:14,134 --> 00:20:15,594
Rule number two?

277
00:20:16,553 --> 00:20:18,305
What was rule number two?

278
00:20:18,389 --> 00:20:19,807
Nobody gets hurt. It's a big one.

279
00:20:19,890 --> 00:20:21,517
Then why isn't it rule number one?

280
00:20:23,227 --> 00:20:24,353
I didn't hurt anybody.

281
00:20:24,436 --> 00:20:25,854
Come on!

282
00:20:26,605 --> 00:20:27,648
BUCKY: Remember me?

283
00:20:29,233 --> 00:20:30,234
I promise.

284
00:20:31,193 --> 00:20:32,528
(GRUNTING)

285
00:20:33,445 --> 00:20:35,406
DR. RAYNOR: And what about
rule number three?

286
00:20:36,949 --> 00:20:41,203
The whole point of making amends
is to fulfill rule number three.

287
00:20:41,286 --> 00:20:42,704
You know, you're a cynic, Doc.

288
00:20:44,206 --> 00:20:46,708
Of course, I completed rule number three.

289
00:20:46,792 --> 00:20:48,502
I am no longer the Winter Soldier.

290
00:20:48,585 --> 00:20:49,837
I am James Bucky Barnes...

291
00:20:49,920 --> 00:20:52,798
And you're part of my efforts
to make amends.

292
00:20:53,590 --> 00:20:55,217
(SIRENS APPROACHING)

293
00:20:55,300 --> 00:20:56,802
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

294
00:20:56,885 --> 00:21:02,724
DR. RAYNOR: <i>So, you did it all right,
but it didn't help with the nightmares.</i>

295
00:21:02,808 --> 00:21:04,893
Well, like I said, I didn't have any.

296
00:21:07,312 --> 00:21:08,313
Look...

297
00:21:09,398 --> 00:21:12,359
one day, you're gonna have to open up

298
00:21:12,443 --> 00:21:16,738
and understand that some people
really do want to help you

299
00:21:16,822 --> 00:21:18,532
and that they can be trusted.

300
00:21:18,615 --> 00:21:20,200
I trust people.

301
00:21:20,784 --> 00:21:21,869
Yeah? Give me your phone.

302
00:21:25,581 --> 00:21:26,582
(BUCKY GROANS)

303
00:21:29,710 --> 00:21:30,794
(DIGITAL BEEPING)

304
00:21:30,878 --> 00:21:32,796
You don't have ten phone numbers
on this thing.

305
00:21:32,880 --> 00:21:34,006
(BEEPING CONTINUES)

306
00:21:34,089 --> 00:21:38,302
Oh, and you've been
ignoring the texts from Sam.

307
00:21:38,927 --> 00:21:39,928
(SMACKS LIPS)

308
00:21:40,012 --> 00:21:41,972
Look, you've gotta nurture friendships.

309
00:21:42,055 --> 00:21:44,933
I am the only person
you have called all week.

310
00:21:45,017 --> 00:21:46,393
- That is so sad.
- (THUDS)

311
00:21:47,978 --> 00:21:49,354
You're alone.

312
00:21:49,438 --> 00:21:51,148
You're a hundred years old.

313
00:21:51,231 --> 00:21:53,442
You have no history, no family...

314
00:21:53,525 --> 00:21:54,776
Are you lashing out at me, Doc?

315
00:21:55,402 --> 00:21:57,404
Because that's
really unprofessional, you know?

316
00:21:57,488 --> 00:21:59,948
When did that start?
Yelling at your clients?

317
00:22:00,032 --> 00:22:01,909
The notebook. That's great. (SIGHS)

318
00:22:03,160 --> 00:22:05,454
All right, give me a break.
I'm trying, okay?

319
00:22:05,537 --> 00:22:06,538
This isn't...

320
00:22:07,122 --> 00:22:09,291
(SIGHS) This is new for me.

321
00:22:09,374 --> 00:22:12,002
I didn't have a moment
to deal with anything, you know?

322
00:22:12,085 --> 00:22:13,212
I had a little...

323
00:22:15,047 --> 00:22:17,216
calm in Wakanda.

324
00:22:18,800 --> 00:22:23,305
And other than that, I just went
from one fight to another for 90 years.

325
00:22:27,643 --> 00:22:30,521
So, now that you've stopped fighting,

326
00:22:31,230 --> 00:22:32,940
what do you want?

327
00:22:38,111 --> 00:22:39,488
Peace.

328
00:22:39,571 --> 00:22:41,573
That is utter bullshit.

329
00:22:41,657 --> 00:22:43,158
You're a terrible shrink.

330
00:22:43,242 --> 00:22:45,160
I was an excellent soldier,

331
00:22:45,244 --> 00:22:48,914
so I saw a lot of dead bodies,
and I know how that can shut you down.

332
00:22:50,123 --> 00:22:51,750
And if you are alone,

333
00:22:52,751 --> 00:22:55,379
that is the quietest, most personal hell.

334
00:22:56,838 --> 00:22:59,007
And, James, it is very hard to escape.

335
00:23:03,011 --> 00:23:05,264
Look, I know that
you have been through a lot,

336
00:23:06,014 --> 00:23:08,100
but you've got your mind back,

337
00:23:09,184 --> 00:23:11,061
you are being pardoned.

338
00:23:11,144 --> 00:23:13,272
I mean, these are good things.

339
00:23:17,484 --> 00:23:18,569
You're free.

340
00:23:21,905 --> 00:23:22,990
To do what?

341
00:23:27,369 --> 00:23:28,579
(CARS HONKING)

342
00:23:30,038 --> 00:23:31,915
Hey, hey, hey! Hey!

343
00:23:32,791 --> 00:23:34,501
What? What?

344
00:23:35,252 --> 00:23:37,588
Your can isn't even half full.
Why don't we just share?

345
00:23:37,671 --> 00:23:40,257
- YORI: What?
- UNIQUE: You don't gotta body me, Yori.

346
00:23:40,340 --> 00:23:41,967
- YORI: It's Mr. Nakajima.
- UNIQUE: Okay.

347
00:23:42,050 --> 00:23:43,594
- Mr. Nakajima!
- Okay. Mr. Nakajima.

348
00:23:43,677 --> 00:23:47,222
Hey! Hey! Yori, what's goin' on?
I thought we're getting lunch.

349
00:23:47,306 --> 00:23:49,558
Unique is putting his trash into my trash.

350
00:23:49,641 --> 00:23:50,642
It's trash.

351
00:23:50,726 --> 00:23:52,811
- And the time has come for me to smack...
- Whoa!

352
00:23:52,894 --> 00:23:54,730
- It's just trash.
- Hang on.

353
00:23:54,813 --> 00:23:56,481
Hey, man. I'm Unique.

354
00:23:56,565 --> 00:23:59,151
It's like Monique, but it's got
a "U" in there for uniqueness.

355
00:23:59,234 --> 00:24:00,652
- That's absurd.
- Okay, sorry.

356
00:24:00,736 --> 00:24:03,071
Yori, you can't keep
fighting with your neighbors.

357
00:24:03,155 --> 00:24:04,990
- Come on, let's get some food.
- No, go away.

358
00:24:05,073 --> 00:24:07,200
But Izzy.
We always go to Izzy on Wednesday.

359
00:24:07,284 --> 00:24:09,494
- I'm not in the mood today.
- Hey, what if I buy?

360
00:24:11,288 --> 00:24:13,665
YORI: Fine, but no talking.

361
00:24:13,749 --> 00:24:15,167
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

362
00:24:15,250 --> 00:24:16,251
Take a look.

363
00:24:17,628 --> 00:24:20,213
Nobody made it past 90 this week.

364
00:24:21,048 --> 00:24:22,758
So young. Such a shame.

365
00:24:23,300 --> 00:24:26,678
You guys didn't order the usual, huh?
Feeling a little adventurous?

366
00:24:28,764 --> 00:24:30,307
You should ask her out.

367
00:24:31,975 --> 00:24:32,976
Mm-mmm...

368
00:24:34,353 --> 00:24:36,480
He would like to take you out on a date.

369
00:24:36,563 --> 00:24:39,900
Maybe to bingo or a night of pinochle?

370
00:24:39,983 --> 00:24:40,984
Pinochle. Yeah.

371
00:24:41,068 --> 00:24:43,862
- I'm really sorry about him.
- Why are you sorry?

372
00:24:43,945 --> 00:24:46,365
- I'm game.
- Wow.

373
00:24:46,448 --> 00:24:49,159
- Tomorrow night, then?
- Tomorrow night's great. (CHUCKLES)

374
00:24:49,242 --> 00:24:50,786
Just maybe not pinochle.

375
00:24:50,869 --> 00:24:52,537
- What's wrong with pinochle?
- Yeah.

376
00:24:52,621 --> 00:24:53,747
I have a shift,

377
00:24:53,830 --> 00:24:56,667
but if you wanna come back here,
I should be done around 10:00.

378
00:25:00,379 --> 00:25:01,880
I can't believe you did that.

379
00:25:01,963 --> 00:25:03,298
It's a dance to these things.

380
00:25:03,382 --> 00:25:07,719
You can't... You gotta warm up
and I haven't danced since 1943...

381
00:25:07,803 --> 00:25:08,804
it feels like.

382
00:25:14,518 --> 00:25:15,519
What's wrong?

383
00:25:18,605 --> 00:25:21,108
(IN JAPANESE) My son...

384
00:25:21,650 --> 00:25:24,736
he loves the red bean mochi.

385
00:25:28,699 --> 00:25:29,700
(IN ENGLISH) Um... (SIGHS)

386
00:25:31,076 --> 00:25:33,995
He had a job with a consulting company.

387
00:25:34,621 --> 00:25:35,622
And, uh,

388
00:25:36,248 --> 00:25:40,127
he was working abroad and he was killed.

389
00:25:41,002 --> 00:25:44,798
The police said
"Wrong place, wrong time," but...

390
00:25:46,049 --> 00:25:48,802
I will never know
what really happened to him.

391
00:25:51,430 --> 00:25:53,056
I felt it was strange.

392
00:25:54,099 --> 00:25:55,100
In here.

393
00:26:35,098 --> 00:26:36,183
This, too, Mom?

394
00:26:36,266 --> 00:26:37,476
SARAH: Yeah, all of it, baby.

395
00:26:37,559 --> 00:26:39,436
And we're taking that one
to the soup kitchen.

396
00:26:39,519 --> 00:26:40,729
So, put that one over there.

397
00:26:42,314 --> 00:26:44,983
Blue for the snapper,
orange for the whitefish.

398
00:26:46,276 --> 00:26:47,444
BOY: Uncle Sam!

399
00:26:48,153 --> 00:26:49,154
What's up?

400
00:26:49,821 --> 00:26:50,822
SARAH: That's right!

401
00:26:51,782 --> 00:26:54,201
Uncle Sam, you're back early.

402
00:26:55,827 --> 00:26:58,622
What's goin' on?
You got Mom's sneaky look on your face.

403
00:26:58,705 --> 00:27:02,042
How you gonna try to read me
when you know I'm the one that reads you?

404
00:27:04,544 --> 00:27:05,712
You gotta marvel at it.

405
00:27:06,546 --> 00:27:09,424
Baby being held together
by duct tape and prayers.

406
00:27:09,966 --> 00:27:12,844
It'll be fine. It just needs to float
long enough for me to sell it.

407
00:27:12,928 --> 00:27:15,430
I thought we were gonna discuss
if we were selling it.

408
00:27:15,514 --> 00:27:16,598
SARAH: We did.

409
00:27:16,681 --> 00:27:19,184
And then you were off fighting
Doctor Space Cape or whatever

410
00:27:19,267 --> 00:27:21,645
while I was holdin' it together
for five long years.

411
00:27:21,728 --> 00:27:23,605
Now that the world
is going back to normal,

412
00:27:23,688 --> 00:27:24,731
this thing's gotta go.

413
00:27:24,815 --> 00:27:26,858
We grew up on this thing.

414
00:27:27,484 --> 00:27:29,903
It's not just Mom and Dad's
name on it, Sarah.

415
00:27:29,986 --> 00:27:31,613
This thing is a part of our family.

416
00:27:31,696 --> 00:27:33,323
You know the situation we're in.

417
00:27:33,406 --> 00:27:36,535
This is why I prefer
not to dwell on it in front of everybody.

418
00:27:36,618 --> 00:27:38,286
Well, what if we don't have to sell it?

419
00:27:38,370 --> 00:27:39,704
Can I talk to you?

420
00:27:39,788 --> 00:27:42,791
- MAN: What's good, Big Sam?
- Oh! What's goin' on, man?

421
00:27:42,874 --> 00:27:45,710
- I'm trying to live like you.
- MAN: You know it. (CHUCKLES)

422
00:27:45,794 --> 00:27:47,420
- Off to save the world again?
- Nah.

423
00:27:47,504 --> 00:27:49,506
Come on, Carlos.
I'm around here more than you.

424
00:27:49,589 --> 00:27:50,799
I'm always reppin' NOLA.

425
00:27:50,882 --> 00:27:53,051
MAN: When you gonna let me
borrow the wings, man?

426
00:27:53,134 --> 00:27:55,887
SAM: As soon as you give my sister back
that $100 you borrowed.

427
00:27:55,971 --> 00:27:58,890
- MAN: That's cold. Now, loan me a hot $50.
- SAM: Yeah. I'll loan you $50.

428
00:28:06,898 --> 00:28:09,025
- Sam, the boat's gotta go.
- SAM: Wait.

429
00:28:09,109 --> 00:28:10,402
No, let me finish.

430
00:28:10,485 --> 00:28:12,904
I'm doin' everything I can
to keep this business afloat.

431
00:28:12,988 --> 00:28:15,073
And every day I'm making $5,
and spending $10.

432
00:28:15,156 --> 00:28:18,118
- So, why won't you let me help?
- No, don't start with that.

433
00:28:18,201 --> 00:28:19,786
We made a deal before Daddy died.

434
00:28:19,870 --> 00:28:22,038
You're out there. I do things my way here.

435
00:28:22,122 --> 00:28:25,333
Right. But you tangled the house
into this when you took those loans.

436
00:28:26,418 --> 00:28:27,502
(GROANS)

437
00:28:28,587 --> 00:28:29,963
Forgot how hard you hit.

438
00:28:30,547 --> 00:28:31,548
Sarah!

439
00:28:33,174 --> 00:28:35,510
Look, and don't hit me again.

440
00:28:37,721 --> 00:28:39,264
What if you had money to fix it up,

441
00:28:39,347 --> 00:28:42,392
make it nice so you can charter it
when you're not out working the waters?

442
00:28:42,475 --> 00:28:45,478
Do you know how hard it was for me
to come to terms with the situation?

443
00:28:46,146 --> 00:28:47,689
Why would you dig this up?

444
00:28:48,732 --> 00:28:51,276
We can take a loan
and consolidate everything.

445
00:28:51,359 --> 00:28:52,819
It'll take down your monthly.

446
00:28:53,945 --> 00:28:56,072
- What?
- You think I didn't try the banks?

447
00:28:56,156 --> 00:28:58,074
They're in with all that big business.

448
00:28:58,158 --> 00:28:59,743
Yeah. But now you have me.

449
00:29:00,827 --> 00:29:01,953
Don't, Sam.

450
00:29:02,037 --> 00:29:03,872
- I just got good with this.
- All right.

451
00:29:03,955 --> 00:29:07,125
- Maybe it is time for us to move on.
- Either way, just let me help.

452
00:29:07,709 --> 00:29:08,877
I'll set the appointment.

453
00:29:10,295 --> 00:29:13,214
Look, I won't let you down.
We can turn this shit around.

454
00:29:13,298 --> 00:29:14,299
Trust me.

455
00:29:17,719 --> 00:29:18,845
To the rescue?

456
00:29:19,346 --> 00:29:20,430
Always.

457
00:29:20,972 --> 00:29:23,058
Now, let's get some dinner. I'm hungry.

458
00:29:39,366 --> 00:29:40,533
(SIREN WAILS)

459
00:29:46,748 --> 00:29:47,999
(DOOR OPENS)

460
00:29:50,085 --> 00:29:51,503
(DOOR CLOSES)

461
00:29:51,586 --> 00:29:53,713
WOMAN: Well,
if that's not the most adorably

462
00:29:53,797 --> 00:29:56,049
old-fashioned thing anyone's ever done.

463
00:30:02,597 --> 00:30:04,349
Grab a seat, I'll be done in a few.

464
00:30:04,432 --> 00:30:05,517
BUCKY: Okay.

465
00:30:08,979 --> 00:30:11,940
So, have you dated much since
half the fish in the sea came back?

466
00:30:12,857 --> 00:30:14,025
BUCKY: Not really.

467
00:30:14,859 --> 00:30:15,860
I, um...

468
00:30:16,695 --> 00:30:18,530
tried the whole online dating thing.

469
00:30:18,613 --> 00:30:20,782
It's pretty crazy.

470
00:30:22,242 --> 00:30:23,576
A lot of weird pictures.

471
00:30:23,660 --> 00:30:25,120
What kind of weird?

472
00:30:26,162 --> 00:30:28,081
I mean, tiger photos?

473
00:30:28,748 --> 00:30:31,334
Half the time I don't even know
what I'm looking at. It's...

474
00:30:32,043 --> 00:30:33,044
It's a lot.

475
00:30:34,462 --> 00:30:36,297
(CHUCKLES) You sound like my dad.

476
00:30:36,381 --> 00:30:37,424
Mmm...

477
00:30:38,550 --> 00:30:39,843
Wait, how old are you?

478
00:30:39,926 --> 00:30:41,428
A hundred and six.

479
00:30:42,637 --> 00:30:45,515
(BOTH LAUGH)

480
00:30:46,891 --> 00:30:48,268
What's up with your gloves?

481
00:30:49,060 --> 00:30:50,145
BUCKY: I, um...

482
00:30:50,729 --> 00:30:52,022
have, uh... (CLICKS TONGUE)

483
00:30:53,440 --> 00:30:54,691
Poor circulation.

484
00:30:54,774 --> 00:30:55,900
WOMAN: Hmm...

485
00:30:58,111 --> 00:30:59,863
- Let's play a game.
- Yeah.

486
00:30:59,946 --> 00:31:02,157
- You like games?
- Love 'em.

487
00:31:03,408 --> 00:31:05,326
We keep some games around
for boring shifts.

488
00:31:05,410 --> 00:31:06,995
I'll go grab a couple of beers.

489
00:31:20,216 --> 00:31:21,217
What are you doing?

490
00:31:21,301 --> 00:31:22,927
I'm reading your mind.

491
00:31:24,054 --> 00:31:25,055
Please don't.

492
00:31:26,222 --> 00:31:27,766
B-8, sucker.

493
00:31:27,849 --> 00:31:30,101
- Uh, hit!
- (CHUCKLES)

494
00:31:31,269 --> 00:31:33,688
- Drink! Come on, drink.
- (BUCKY SIGHS)

495
00:31:33,772 --> 00:31:34,856
All right. Okay.

496
00:31:35,982 --> 00:31:38,068
Wow, you really can drink.

497
00:31:38,151 --> 00:31:40,028
( INHALES) Yeah, well...

498
00:31:40,111 --> 00:31:41,654
Do you have any siblings?

499
00:31:41,738 --> 00:31:43,323
I have a sister. F-4.

500
00:31:43,406 --> 00:31:44,699
Miss. Drink.

501
00:31:45,742 --> 00:31:47,118
Are you close with your parents?

502
00:31:47,952 --> 00:31:49,704
(SIGHS) I was.

503
00:31:49,788 --> 00:31:50,789
They passed away.

504
00:31:50,872 --> 00:31:53,333
(CLICKS TONGUE) Um, D-5.

505
00:31:53,416 --> 00:31:54,959
Oh, I'm sorry.

506
00:31:55,043 --> 00:31:56,878
Um, miss.

507
00:31:58,630 --> 00:32:01,341
I think it's really sweet
you're spending time with Yori.

508
00:32:02,634 --> 00:32:05,220
It's been hard for him since his son died.

509
00:32:06,721 --> 00:32:09,849
I think not knowing how it happened
is the hardest part for him.

510
00:32:11,101 --> 00:32:12,852
Mmm, it really messed him up.

511
00:32:15,563 --> 00:32:18,316
You know how you call a guy
whose wife died a widower?

512
00:32:18,399 --> 00:32:21,027
Or, if your parents die, you're an orphan.

513
00:32:22,070 --> 00:32:26,741
You know, there's no word
for someone whose kids die.

514
00:32:27,283 --> 00:32:29,327
Because it's the worst thing
that could happen.

515
00:32:29,410 --> 00:32:30,745
Yeah, excuse me.

516
00:32:30,829 --> 00:32:32,288
You good?

517
00:32:41,714 --> 00:32:42,882
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

518
00:32:42,966 --> 00:32:44,050
(DOOR OPENS)

519
00:32:44,634 --> 00:32:47,053
Hey, what are you doing here?

520
00:32:49,222 --> 00:32:50,431
How was the date?

521
00:32:58,773 --> 00:33:00,275
It was... It was good.

522
00:33:05,155 --> 00:33:06,739
Forgot I owed you for lunch.

523
00:33:27,051 --> 00:33:28,136
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

524
00:33:32,599 --> 00:33:33,892
SAM: There we go.

525
00:33:33,975 --> 00:33:36,436
Get the plates moving.
Get some rice in there. Come on.

526
00:33:36,519 --> 00:33:38,021
SARAH: Oh, lined up perfectly.

527
00:33:38,521 --> 00:33:40,148
You always gotta do the most, huh?

528
00:33:40,231 --> 00:33:42,734
I don't play
with these White folks. (CHUCKLES)

529
00:33:42,817 --> 00:33:46,821
Look, I know you're worried, all right?
But I did the research. I ran the numbers.

530
00:33:46,905 --> 00:33:48,948
- You think this is gonna work?
- I know it will.

531
00:33:49,032 --> 00:33:51,409
And then we can renovate the kitchen.

532
00:33:51,492 --> 00:33:54,829
Now, you said you wanted
to sell plates on the weekends, right?

533
00:33:54,913 --> 00:33:58,291
That's great. You can introduce
some of Grandma's recipes and...

534
00:33:58,374 --> 00:33:59,918
Shit. We gotta go.

535
00:34:00,668 --> 00:34:02,378
Wait, the appointment's in an hour.

536
00:34:02,462 --> 00:34:06,883
There's no such thing as on time.
You're either early or late. Pick one.

537
00:34:06,966 --> 00:34:09,552
Okay. Now you're
really doing more than the most.

538
00:34:09,636 --> 00:34:11,304
All right, boys, I love you.

539
00:34:11,387 --> 00:34:16,267
Now, Mr. Liu's gonna watch over you
and no video games.

540
00:34:16,351 --> 00:34:18,019
- Love you. Bye.
- Bye.

541
00:34:18,102 --> 00:34:19,854
BOTH: Yes, video games.

542
00:34:20,688 --> 00:34:21,981
(SAM CHUCKLES)

543
00:34:22,065 --> 00:34:24,692
- Three, two, one.
- (DOOR SLAMS)

544
00:34:24,776 --> 00:34:26,194
Go, go, go!

545
00:34:34,494 --> 00:34:35,912
( INDISTINCT CHATTER)

546
00:34:53,471 --> 00:34:56,140
(IN GERMAN)
Do you know what we're supposed to do?

547
00:34:56,849 --> 00:34:58,393
(DISTANT WHISTLING)

548
00:35:06,234 --> 00:35:07,694
( INDISTINCT CHATTER)

549
00:35:15,368 --> 00:35:16,619
(CELL PHONE BEEPS)

550
00:35:17,453 --> 00:35:19,038
(GLASS BREAKING)

551
00:35:19,122 --> 00:35:20,623
(CROWD CLAMORING)

552
00:35:23,960 --> 00:35:25,169
(ALARM RINGING)

553
00:35:34,387 --> 00:35:35,680
(IN GERMAN) He has the money!

554
00:35:39,976 --> 00:35:41,102
(WOMAN PANTING)

555
00:35:45,773 --> 00:35:46,858
You are under arrest!

556
00:35:46,941 --> 00:35:48,484
(TORRES IN ENGLISH) He's getting away!

557
00:35:48,568 --> 00:35:49,902
(GRUNTS)

558
00:35:49,986 --> 00:35:52,572
TORRES: Sorry. Uh... (IN GERMAN) Sorry.

559
00:35:52,655 --> 00:35:54,282
( INDISTINCT CHATTER)

560
00:35:55,950 --> 00:35:57,285
(BOTH GRUNTING)

561
00:35:58,036 --> 00:36:00,663
- (MAN SCREAMS)
- (GRUNTS)

562
00:36:00,747 --> 00:36:02,707
(IN ENGLISH) Hey, hey, hey!

563
00:36:03,791 --> 00:36:07,462
I don't know how jurisdiction works here,
but I'mma have to place you under arrest.

564
00:36:07,545 --> 00:36:08,588
(GROANS)

565
00:36:10,340 --> 00:36:11,841
(BOTH GRUNTING)

566
00:36:11,924 --> 00:36:13,509
(GROANS)

567
00:36:15,053 --> 00:36:16,804
- (MAN GRUNTS)
- (GROANS)

568
00:36:31,444 --> 00:36:34,322
Sorry, I keep thinking.
Did you used to play for LSU?

569
00:36:34,405 --> 00:36:36,324
- (CHUCKLES)
- Do I know you from somewhere?

570
00:36:36,407 --> 00:36:37,575
I don't know. Do you?

571
00:36:37,658 --> 00:36:39,744
I do. But where?

572
00:36:40,286 --> 00:36:41,287
Come on.

573
00:36:44,624 --> 00:36:46,000
- I knew it. Falcon!
- Yeah! (LAUGHS)

574
00:36:46,084 --> 00:36:49,253
Yes! Yes! Man! (CHUCKLING) Oh...

575
00:36:49,337 --> 00:36:51,631
I didn't want to say anything. You know...

576
00:36:51,714 --> 00:36:53,383
I always wanted to be an Avenger.

577
00:36:53,466 --> 00:36:56,135
Oh, man, it's a dream come true, you know?

578
00:36:56,219 --> 00:36:57,261
(CHUCKLES) That's amazing.

579
00:36:57,345 --> 00:36:59,430
Like, keeping my family's business afloat

580
00:36:59,514 --> 00:37:02,058
by changin' to
a fishin' and charter model.

581
00:37:02,141 --> 00:37:04,769
I've always wondered...
How do you guys make a living?

582
00:37:04,852 --> 00:37:08,189
Those guys or the guy sitting
in front of you tryin' to get a loan?

583
00:37:08,272 --> 00:37:09,607
Both. (CHUCKLES)

584
00:37:09,690 --> 00:37:12,026
I mean, your financials
are all over the place.

585
00:37:12,110 --> 00:37:14,028
Is there some kind of fund for heroes?

586
00:37:14,112 --> 00:37:15,822
Or did Stark pay you when he was around?

587
00:37:15,905 --> 00:37:17,115
My condolences, by the way.

588
00:37:17,198 --> 00:37:19,450
Thank you, but no,
it doesn't really work like that.

589
00:37:19,534 --> 00:37:21,702
There's a tremendous amount of goodwill

590
00:37:21,786 --> 00:37:25,331
and because of that,
people are inclined to help,

591
00:37:25,415 --> 00:37:27,875
- which applies to the business.
- Yeah, right.

592
00:37:27,959 --> 00:37:30,503
But were you living off
of goodwill this whole time?

593
00:37:30,586 --> 00:37:32,505
I don't get what you're going for here.

594
00:37:32,588 --> 00:37:35,550
Are you trying to help us, or indict us?

595
00:37:35,633 --> 00:37:38,845
You have no income
over the last five years.

596
00:37:38,928 --> 00:37:40,638
How can you have income
if you don't exist?

597
00:37:40,721 --> 00:37:41,722
SAM: Sarah.

598
00:37:43,558 --> 00:37:44,559
Uh...

599
00:37:45,351 --> 00:37:49,605
(STUTTERS) I've been gone
like several billion other people.

600
00:37:49,689 --> 00:37:51,232
But if you look at our plan,

601
00:37:51,315 --> 00:37:54,402
I have government contracts,
so, that's proof of earnings.

602
00:37:54,485 --> 00:37:57,488
And I know for a fact
that we qualify for a SBA loan.

603
00:37:57,572 --> 00:37:59,615
Under the old terms, sure.

604
00:37:59,699 --> 00:38:02,326
But these days, what,
with everyone just showing up,

605
00:38:02,410 --> 00:38:04,412
well, things tightened up.

606
00:38:04,495 --> 00:38:07,123
Funny how things always tighten around us.

607
00:38:07,206 --> 00:38:10,877
Easy there. Look, I'm on your side.
After all, he's a hero.

608
00:38:12,503 --> 00:38:14,380
Is there any chance,
and you could say "no,"

609
00:38:14,464 --> 00:38:16,466
that I could get a selfie
with your arms out?

610
00:38:16,549 --> 00:38:17,550
- Are you serious?
- (LAUGHS)

611
00:38:21,012 --> 00:38:23,389
Mr. Wilson, Mrs. Wilson...

612
00:38:23,473 --> 00:38:25,475
Miss. I'm a widow.

613
00:38:25,558 --> 00:38:27,059
Ms. Wilson.

614
00:38:28,019 --> 00:38:31,522
I know your family
has banked with us for generations,

615
00:38:31,606 --> 00:38:33,065
but we cannot approve you.

616
00:38:34,692 --> 00:38:36,027
I'm truly sorry.

617
00:38:41,491 --> 00:38:45,203
We're gonna get that loan. I don't care
if I have to go to every bank in the city.

618
00:38:45,286 --> 00:38:47,455
Sam, stop!
I don't want to deal with this again.

619
00:38:47,538 --> 00:38:49,290
That's what life is, dealing with things.

620
00:38:49,373 --> 00:38:52,835
You are so out of pocket for that.
Don't forget, you joined the Air Force.

621
00:38:52,919 --> 00:38:55,171
You didn't see everything
Mom and Daddy dealt with.

622
00:38:56,005 --> 00:38:58,591
I knew they weren't gonna help us.
It's not their job.

623
00:38:58,674 --> 00:39:01,135
Those people don't know who Daddy was,
and he was a giant.

624
00:39:01,219 --> 00:39:02,845
I don't care. I'm not gonna quit.

625
00:39:02,929 --> 00:39:05,598
What are you trying to prove?
And who you trying to prove it to?

626
00:39:05,681 --> 00:39:08,267
- I swear, after Daddy died...
- I knew that was gonna come up.

627
00:39:08,351 --> 00:39:12,396
I never hid what I thought. You had
to go off and fight armies and monsters.

628
00:39:12,480 --> 00:39:13,481
And I appreciate that,

629
00:39:13,564 --> 00:39:16,442
but you don't get to come back here
and try to right your wrongs

630
00:39:16,526 --> 00:39:19,111
just because you couldn't
deal with what was going on here.

631
00:39:19,195 --> 00:39:21,489
You don't know what happened
these last five years.

632
00:39:21,572 --> 00:39:24,325
I was alone with two babies
and I survived.

633
00:39:24,867 --> 00:39:26,744
I'm the one
who kept that boat from sinkin'.

634
00:39:26,827 --> 00:39:29,372
Yeah, well, half the boat's mine
and so is the house.

635
00:39:29,455 --> 00:39:31,541
We're not sellin' our family's legacy.

636
00:39:31,624 --> 00:39:33,751
You gonna do me like that
when you know I'm right?

637
00:39:33,834 --> 00:39:34,877
SAM: Yep!

638
00:39:36,003 --> 00:39:37,338
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

639
00:39:41,634 --> 00:39:42,635
Okay.

640
00:39:45,429 --> 00:39:47,181
(PIPES CREAKING)

641
00:39:47,265 --> 00:39:48,307
(SIGHS)

642
00:39:50,977 --> 00:39:51,978
Oh!

643
00:39:53,145 --> 00:39:56,607
(EXHALES) Come on, baby.
What you got for me?

644
00:39:57,692 --> 00:39:58,901
(ENGINE SPUTTERS)

645
00:40:00,486 --> 00:40:01,571
Come on! Come on!

646
00:40:01,654 --> 00:40:03,531
(ENGINE SPUTTERS)

647
00:40:03,614 --> 00:40:04,615
Shit!

648
00:40:05,575 --> 00:40:06,659
(WATER SPLASHING)

649
00:40:08,703 --> 00:40:10,621
(BOAT CREAKING)

650
00:40:21,132 --> 00:40:22,133
(CELL PHONE DINGS)

651
00:40:28,180 --> 00:40:29,390
(DINGS)

652
00:40:30,683 --> 00:40:31,684
(KEYBOARD CLACKING)

653
00:40:40,693 --> 00:40:43,112
SAM: So, this is the leader
of the Flag Smashers, huh?

654
00:40:43,195 --> 00:40:44,572
<i>Yeah, real nice guy.</i>

655
00:40:44,655 --> 00:40:47,533
I thought you were
supposed to be monitoring them online.

656
00:40:47,617 --> 00:40:49,118
<i>I was. I did.</i>

657
00:40:49,201 --> 00:40:51,454
<i>But you know sometimes you gotta
get your hands dirty,</i>

658
00:40:51,537 --> 00:40:53,039
<i>- or a broken orbital.</i>
- (SAM SCOFFS)

659
00:40:53,122 --> 00:40:54,832
You're lucky that's all you got.

660
00:40:55,499 --> 00:40:56,500
He's strong.

661
00:40:56,584 --> 00:40:59,670
He was. I mean, bro,
they went dark as soon as it was all over.

662
00:40:59,754 --> 00:41:00,755
But that's their M.O.

663
00:41:00,838 --> 00:41:03,924
We gotta keep our eyes and ears
to the ground till they pop up again.

664
00:41:04,008 --> 00:41:05,926
Anything else happen outside the video?

665
00:41:06,010 --> 00:41:09,388
<i>No, man. My face was in the dirt
before I knew what was happening.</i>

666
00:41:10,306 --> 00:41:11,807
<i>Why? What are you thinking?</i>

667
00:41:13,351 --> 00:41:14,435
Nothin'.

668
00:41:15,978 --> 00:41:17,855
<i>Wait. You don't think he could be a...</i>

669
00:41:17,938 --> 00:41:19,607
Look, I'll circle back to you.

670
00:41:19,690 --> 00:41:22,526
- Let's keep this between me and you, okay?
- TORRES: <i>All right.</i>

671
00:41:22,610 --> 00:41:25,071
SARAH: Oh, my God, Sam.
You better look at this.

672
00:41:25,154 --> 00:41:27,573
(MAN ON TV) <i>Unrest,
in the wake of recent events</i>

673
00:41:27,657 --> 00:41:29,325
<i>has left us vulnerable.</i>

674
00:41:29,909 --> 00:41:32,078
<i>Every day Americans feel it.</i>

675
00:41:32,662 --> 00:41:37,500
<i>While we love heroes who put
their lives on the line to defend Earth,</i>

676
00:41:37,583 --> 00:41:40,252
<i>we also need a hero
to defend this country.</i>

677
00:41:41,045 --> 00:41:46,509
We need a real person
who embodies America's greatest values.

678
00:41:47,426 --> 00:41:50,930
<i>We need someone to inspire us again,</i>

679
00:41:51,681 --> 00:41:55,643
<i>someone who can be a symbol for all of us.</i>

680
00:41:55,726 --> 00:42:00,815
<i>So, on behalf of the Department of Defense
and our Commander-in-Chief,</i>

681
00:42:00,898 --> 00:42:04,568
<i>it is with great honor
that we announce here today</i>

682
00:42:04,652 --> 00:42:09,532
<i>that the United States of America
has a new hero.</i>

683
00:42:09,615 --> 00:42:13,119
Join me in welcoming
your new Captain America.

684
00:42:13,202 --> 00:42:14,662
(ALL CHEERING)

685
00:42:38,686 --> 00:42:40,688
(MUSIC PLAYING)

